                            <comment id="120601" author="josephw" created="Fri, 16 Oct 2015 15:00:59 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This is similar to &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/browse/SPR-6706&quot; title=&quot;Add conversion support for Joda Duration and Period&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;SPR-6706&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;SPR-6706&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, but only for &lt;tt&gt;java.time&lt;/tt&gt;, rather than JODA.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="120621" author="josephw" created="Sat, 17 Oct 2015 06:36:50 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;PR: &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-framework/pull/891&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;SPR-13579: Support conversion from Strings to Java 8 Durations.&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="133297" author="pofin" created="Wed, 9 Nov 2016 20:44:24 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hi,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I, too,  started to use &lt;tt&gt;Duration&lt;/tt&gt; for configuration properties rather than things like &quot;someTimoutMillis&quot;. I realized Spring does not offer out-of-the-box conversion from String to Duration, at least not when using &lt;tt&gt;context:property-override&lt;/tt&gt;, so a created a PR &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-framework/pull/1231&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-framework/pull/1231&lt;/a&gt; &amp;#8211; all this before finding this issue.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This issue is closed, but I tested Spring master branch and couldn&apos;t get expected behavior (no conversion was found) before applying my patch. I see &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=josephw&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;josephw&quot;&gt;Joseph Walton&lt;/a&gt; adds completely different class than my PR, so I guess this isn&apos;t equivalent, Maybe I understand &quot;conversion&quot; differently than this issue. &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=juergen.hoeller&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;juergen.hoeller&quot;&gt;Juergen Hoeller&lt;/a&gt; could you please have a look?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="133657" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Fri, 25 Nov 2016 16:35:38 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;~pofin&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt;, we&apos;re only supporting &lt;tt&gt;Duration&lt;/tt&gt; and &lt;tt&gt;Period&lt;/tt&gt; in &lt;tt&gt;org.springframework.format&lt;/tt&gt;&apos;s JSR-310 package at this point, along with the general date-time types, analogous to Joda-Time. The ISO text representations for date-time types are arguably rather serialization-oriented and not really intuitive for user-driven configuration purposes, which is why we haven&apos;t added them to the core property editors.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you&apos;d like to enable such ISO formatting rules for configuration purposes, set up your application context with a &lt;tt&gt;DefaultFormattingConversionService&lt;/tt&gt; out of the box, e.g. a bean with name &quot;conversionService&quot; which will get picked up for bean property values as well then.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="133659" author="pofin" created="Fri, 25 Nov 2016 21:30:41 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=juergen.hoeller&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;juergen.hoeller&quot;&gt;Juergen Hoeller&lt;/a&gt;, thanks for your response. I didn&apos;t know about formatters and that they can be plugged as property editors. Thanks for explaining this to me.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;The ISO text representations for date-time types are arguably rather serialization-oriented and not really intuitive for user-driven configuration purposes&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I couldn&apos;t disagree. So what do you think about arguably more intuitive format (e.g. &quot;12 s&quot;) provided as property editor, with the intention to cover said configuration purposes? Would such a think find its place in Spring?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
